100 Days of DevOps ‚Äî Day 20(20/100)

1Ô∏è‚É£ What is OOMKilled?

A container is OOMKilled when it exceeds its memory limit.
The OS kills it to protect the node.

OOMKilled means Out Of Memory Killed.

‚∏ª

2Ô∏è‚É£ What is the Kubernetes Scheduler?

The Scheduler decides which node a pod runs on.
It checks resource availability and scheduling rules.

‚∏ª

3Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Node Selector?

Node Selector binds a pod to nodes using labels.
It‚Äôs the simplest scheduling constraint in Kubernetes.

‚∏ª

4Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Taint?

A taint prevents pods from landing on a node.
Only pods with matching tolerations can run there.

‚∏ª

5Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Toleration?

Tolerations allow pods to run on tainted nodes.
They don‚Äôt force scheduling but remove the block.

‚∏ª

6Ô∏è‚É£ What is NoSchedule?

NoSchedule prevents pods from being scheduled on the node.
Only pods with matching tolerations can still run there.

‚∏ª

7Ô∏è‚É£ What is NoExecute?

NoExecute blocks new pods and evicts existing ones.
Pods must have tolerations to stay or be scheduled.

‚∏ª

8Ô∏è‚É£ What is PreferNoSchedule?

PreferNoSchedule is a soft block ‚Äî scheduler tries to avoid the node.
Pods may still run if no better node is available.

‚∏ª

9Ô∏è‚É£ What is Affinity?

Affinity sets rules to place pods on certain nodes.
It controls pod placement using required/preferred conditions.

‚∏ª

üîü What is Anti-Affinity?

Anti-affinity ensures pods do NOT run together on the same node.
It helps with high availability and spreading workloads.

